{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_protoss_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280656239/1908032201/0673.xml":{"full_text":"IOWA HO.iOiS HUGHES\nCummins Praises Him at the\nSociety Dinner. CHEERS\nFOR ROOSEVELT\nGen. Grenville Dodge Presided at\nBanquet.\nRAILROAD RATES AND PASSES\nCauses of the Recent Financial\nTroubles Discussed?Welcome to\nthe Speaker.\nNEW YORK. March 21.?Govs. Albert\nB. Cummins of Iowa and Charles E.\nHughes of New York were the guests of\nhonor at the third annual banquet of the\nIowa Society of New York at the Hotel\nPlaza tonight. ]?ach received a flattering\nreception, but the name that was reeeived\nwith general acclaim throughout\nthe after-dinner proceedings was that of\nPresident Roosevelt.\nGen. Grenville M. Dodge, who presided,\nstarted the enthusiasm for the President,\nwhen, in calling for a toast to be drunk\nto him, he said tnat in Iowa Roosevelt\nranked with Washington, Lincoln, Grant\nand McKinley. The diners rose and\n\ncheers rang out that were long and\nhearty.\nWelcome to Cummins.\nGov. Cummins, who later responded to\nthe toast \"Iowa,\" was given an option\nwhen he rose to speak. He paid a compliment\nto Gov. Hughes, who did not ar*\nrive in the banquet hall until later, for\nhis work in the insurance investigation\nand then plunged into a eulogy of President\nRoosevelt, saying:\n\"We cheered anciher eminent son of\nNew York as he bo dly struck out through\n?IIJ ?eta toyman\nan unexpiorea nuuci ucoa ui\nship, guided only by the compass of conscience.\nand we are cheering him still.\nOur people never tire in their acclaim. All\nhail to Theodore Roosevelt.\"\nThe remainder of his speech was given\nover to the subject of Iowa's legislation\nin regard to corporations and a discussion\nof the causes of the financial troubles.\nGov. Cummins said in part:\nPraise for Roosevelt.\n\"We applauded Charles E. Hughes as\nhe laid bare the wickedness of men\ncharged with the most sacred trust that\ncan be committed to morta hands. We\ncheered another eminent son of New\nYork as he boldly struck out through an\nunexplored wilderness of statesmanship,\nguided by the compass of conscience, and\nwe are cheering him still. Our people\nnever tire in their acclaim. All hall to\nDn/.cowan It iR said that he\nA li<OVUVI A?w/uv v? v?\nhas made mistakes; I suppose he has; but\nthe mistakes of a man trying to find a\nsafe path are better than the Inaction of\na man who shrinks away, saying 'There\nIs no path let us be content as we are.'\nIt is said that he talks too much. It may\nbe so, but I would rather hear the voice\nof a man declaring what he believes to\nbe true, even if he is wrong, than to\nlisten to the platitudes of the man who\nIs too cowardly or too conservative to\nsay anything.\"\nOn the subject of Iowa's legislation\nagainst corporations Gov. Cummins said.\nBailroad Legislation.\n\"We have enacted a primary election\nlaw that will destroy their (the corporation's)\npower in caucuses. I hope this\ndid not affect Wall street. We enacted\nIo^mt fophMrHno' all /*nntr4hittinna Kv\npo rat ions for political purposes. With\nhonest people this ought to have enhanced\nrather than diminished the value\nof their stocks. We enacted a law prohibiting\nrailways from issu'ng free transportation\nto any persons Rave officers and\nemployers in continuous service. This\nmay?I hope it will?lessen their political\nactivity, but it will not reduce their revenues.\nWe enacted a law giving our railroad\ncommission the authority to establish\njoint rates. This was doing no more\nthan to secure for ourselves a privilege\nthat the railways had voluntarily conferred\nupon nearly every other community\nin the country. We could discover no\nreason why we should be ground between\nthe upper and the nether millstones.\n\"We enacted a law fixing sixteen hours\nas the limit for continuous work in the\noperation of trains, and no one has questioned\nits wisdom. We enacted a law\nrequiring railways to keep their rights\nof way free of dry grass and weeds as\nprotection against fire, and this every\nprogressive railway had long been doing.\nWe enacted a law making it obligatory\nto put in cattle guards at farm crossings,\nand this every fair railway had\nfor years been doing.\nThe Two-Cent Bate.\n\"Finally, we enacted a law making 2\ncents a mile the maximum passenger fare\nupon our first-class roads. We did this\nnot to reduce revenues, but to remove discrimination.\nA great many of our people\nwho could best afford to pay were traveling\nfor nothing on passes. A great many\nmore wno had money enough to buy a\nmileage book were traveling at 2 cents per\nmile. The remainder of our people, those\nwho could least afford to pay, were traveling\nat 3 cents a mile. The average rate\nreceived was a little less than 2 cents, and\nall we did was to say: 'Make all your\npassengers pay the same rate.'\n\"We enacted a \"law that is Intended to\nkeep our water in our streams instead of\nIn our corporate stocks. I think it is a\ngood law, but. if it is not JCew Jersey is\nstill open to the promoter.\"\nNeed for Honesty.\nAs to the causes of the financial troubles,\nthe governor said:\n\"Look rather to a system which has\npermitted reckless men to flood the country\nand its markets with worthless and\nbaseless stocks and inadequately protected\nbonds; look rather to a system which\nIn our stock exchanges makes one-half\nthe memhers irrmlarnhlo enemli?B of ovprv\ncorporation whose stocks are listed for\npurchase or sale; look rather to a system\nof banking which at the very moment\nwhen banks are most needed compels\nthem to suspend their most important\nfunctions, and. ahove all and beyond all.\nlook at the spirit which has repudiated\nthe eternal, and. in the end. overpowering.\ntruth, that s able, permanent wealth\nmn be produced only by honest, faithful\ntabor.\"\nSTERHETT MAKES RECORD.\nSuccess of G. W. U. Pole Vaulter at\nRichmond.\nSi^'lal Dispatch to The Star.\nRICHMOND. Va.. March iil.?By a good\nmargin of 17 points the stalwart athletes\nof the University of Virginia won the cup\nat the Indoor track meet here this evening.\nRector easily won all the dashes in\nwhich he entered, but was beaten in the\n4-K>yard dash by Louthan of Richmond\nCollege, who also won the 8S0-yard run\nIn a great burst of speed. Sterrett, the\nGeorge Washington star pole vaulter. was\nanother feature, easily winning the pole\nvault, clea-ing the bar at 11 feet, making\na new southern collegiate record. Martin\nof Virginia won the hurdle race and\nwas conspicuous in other events. There\nwas some disappointment when it was announced\nthat the Georgetown relay team\nhad missed the train and their race with\nRichmond College was declared off. The\nWashington School for Boys also failed to\nshow up.\nf\nSPEAKERS A'\nyy. ^niB|\nMKagaBwMHr g a.MHWtTasMaBMSsi\ni3enngj2v.1s szxmn\nof nebraska\nGOOD TIMESDAWN1NG|\nProphecy at Dinner of the\nBeta Pi Club.\nABLE SPEAKERS PRESENT\n___??.\nRepresentative Bontell Sounds a\nHopeful Note.\n1\nBORAH ON THE LATE PANIC\n\nRecent Legislation and Its Effect on\nthe Country?Sanity of the\nCommon People.\n\nNEW YORK, March 21?Two United\nStates senators?W. E. Borah of Idaho\nand Norris Brown of Nebraska?and one\nmember of the National House of Representatives.\nHenry Sherman Boutell of Illinois,\nwere the guests of honor and chief\nspeakers at the dinner of the Beta Theta\nPI Club at the Hotel Astor tonight. Optimistic\nsentiments as to the early return\nof prosperity to the country and expreseiniiQ\nof that 1 <vcrlolatinn c\\f ra.\ncent years would have a far-reaching and\nlasting effect for the good of the nation\nwas the spirit of the speeches.\n\"Equality Before the Law\" was Senator\nBrown's subject, and he declared for a\nrevision of tbe tariff, urging the formation\nof a tariff commission which should\nbring its report before Congress for intelligent\naction by that body. Senator\nBorah talked on \"The Recent Panic and\nIts Lessons,\" while Mr. Boutell took recent\nlegislation and its good effects as a\nsubject.\nJustice Scudder of the supreme court\nABRUZZI SAILS AWAY\nUNDERSTOOD EMMANUEL AP-\nPROVES MARRIAGE PLANS.\nROME, March 21.?The following is a\nsemi-official statement:\nxne Kin^ nas Deen linuraieu uj me\nDuke of the Abruzzi of his desirs to\n-narry M'ss Elkins.\nKins Emmanuel never offered opposition;\nhe only wished not to hasten nat- j\nters, and made the stipulattion that ev?-y- j\nthing should be arranged with calmness\nand dignity, in order to give the marriage\na fitting solemnity. j\nMeanwhile public opinion in Amerfca\nshould be calm. When the Duke of tie i\nAbruzzi returns to Rome all details wll\nbe arranged if the duke persists in ha\nintention. He will return to America h\nthe autumn, accompanied by the Duk>\nd'Aosta. The Count of Turin, who wil\nrepresent the king at the wedding, said\nstrictly speaking, the marriage should\ntake place in Rome, but for various reasons\nthe king would rather have it performed\nin America.\nHunting No Fortune.\nOn arrival of the bridal couple in Rome\nthere will be a formal transcription of the\nmarriage in the registers of the royal\nfamily in the presence of the king, queen,\nprincess and ministers Miss Elkins will\nhave until autumn to become a convert\nto Catholicism. The pope will authorize\nthe Archbishop of New York to efTect the\nconversion. An official announcement of\nthe betrothal will be published two weeks\nbefore the marriage.\nThere is great indignation in court circles\nagainst the reports in American papers\nthat the duke is making the marriage\na question of money, and insists on\na dowry. The prefect of the palace said\ntoday:\n\"In Europe nobody would conceive such\nI absurdities An Italian prince has no\nneed to seek a wealthy heiress. Besides\nthe Duke of the Abruzzi is one of the\nrichest European princes. The American\npapers also make too much of a fuss over\nthe question of titles and rights. There's\nreally no such question. Whoever raaries\nAbruzzi will become her royal highness.\nDuchess of the Abruzzi. The king\nis very much annoyed uy the extrava- I\ngances of the American press.\"\nDuke Is Silent.\nNEW tORK. March 21.?The Duke of\nthe Abruzzi, who smilingly refused to be\ninterviewed at 12:55 o'clock this morning\nwhen lie boardeji the Cunarder Lusitania.\ndid not change his mind before the liner\nsailed at 8 o'clock. He stayed in his\ncabin and sent word by his vaiet that he\nwould say no more than he had said a ready.\nHe called for all the morning\nnewspapers and was seen reading then\nwith evident amusement. About\nItalians were on the pier hoping to get a\nglimpse of the duke when the liner drew\nout into the stream, but he did not come\non deck. His secretary said that the\nduke would not discuss the subject of h'r\nengagement to Miss Elkins, daughter of\nSenator Elkins of West Vlrgin'a.\nDistrict Pair Wed in Baltimore.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nBALTIMORE. Md.. March 21 A mar\nage license was issued here today to\n\"dward J. Fitzgibbons, aged twenty-one\ni vears, and Mazzie M. Humphreys, aged\ni dneteen years. The couple hail from\ni Washington, D. C.t the prospective bridei\ntrooni giving his address as 919 9th street\nnortheast\nr THE BETA THET/\n<19\nwmSW 9BM\n^\"BKl^aRjjMpMMM^. H\n^^BSaSfifea\n<5en. WE.Tks&Ji\nofJzmo.\nacted as toastmaster and introduced p\nRepresentative Boutell as the first p\nspeaker.\nRepresentative Boutell's Remarks. i t\nIn responding to the toast \"The Ship of p\nState.\" Mr. Boutell said: \"If we call the c\nPresident the captain of the ship of state i t\nwe must assign to the. Speaker of the c\nHouse the title and honors of the Pilot, f\nAt no time in her long cruise has our ship\nof state been in charge of braver or more\nskillful navigators than her present cap- fc\ntain and pilot, Roosevelt and Cannon. Al- c\nthough differing widely in many impor- p\ntant traits of character they have in common\nqne of the dominant features of all p\ntruly great minds, downright sincerity. a\n\"During the past five years more legisla- g\ntion of permanent, far-reaching value has c\nbeen enacted by Congress than in all the t\nother years since th#civil war period. In t\nworking out this remedial legislation the t\nPresident and the Speaker have worked c\nin close harmony. Each has generously h\naccorded to the other full recognition and r\npraise of the value of his services.\"\nHe paid a high tribute to the success of o\nPresident Roosevelt's financial policies. a\nIn lliw our interest-bearing debt was v\n$1,046,000,000 and the annual interest was 0\nover $40,000,000. Today the interest-bear- u\ning debt is only $898,000,000, of which $35.000,000\nare Panama bonds; our annual in- a\nterest chaise is only $24,000,000; there is -p\nover one Vjfiiion in gold in the Treasury q\nand an available cash balance of $268,000,- f\n000 over and above the $150,000,000 gold p\nreserve, while our two per cent bonds are 0\nselling at 104. Xo nation in the world can c\nmake anything like such a showing of a\nfinancial strength. j s\nMr. Boutell pointed out that, while in <3\n1900 there were 3,816 national banks using t\n$380,00o,000 of government bonds to secure 0\ncirculation and deposits, there are now 0\n6,600 national banks using $700,000,000 in b\ngovernment bonds to cover circulation\nand deposits. There are now less than a\n$200,000,000 of United States bonds that h\nare not in the hands of national banks; t\nwhile at the same time the national banks s\nare using $250 000,000 of other collateral s\nthan United States bonds to secure gov- n\nernment deposits and their circulation. In b\nother words, there are not enough United tl\nStates bonds outstanding to form the t\nbasis of our national banking system under\nexisting laws. 6\nSenator Borah was the next speaker, g\nHe said, in part: a\nSenator Borah's Remarks.\n\"A few weeks ago we had a panic?a i<\nwell-dressed, highly aristocrat!^ thor-\noughly high-toned panic. F#ery one\nparticipating in the panic was many p\n11: n>alLi>acrvantoH r>nn\nlimes a milium an C~\"<1 vvv*t vw??- I\nservative man of business and a reac- b\ntionary in politics. What caused the a\nSENATOR TILLMAN IS ILL I\nSEVERE RECURRENCE OF AN 1\nOLD NERVOUS TROUBLE.\nPhysician's Statement Says Attack n\nWas Due to Heat and Overwork. a\nIs Now Better.\nJ'\nb\nCOLUMBIA, S. C., March 21.?United G\n\n3tates Senator Benjamin R. Tillman is\nseriously ill at his home at Trenton, this\nstate, suffering with a nervous attack, o\nJue, it is believed by his physicians, from\nf\nhard work.\nA ervnoUncr in Wucln'nctnn \\fnnHflV\nm kci oyv untug *u uuiitttg\nthe senator went to Clemson College to\nattend a meeting of the board of trustees 1\nof that institution. When he reached a\nhome Thursday night he had an attack, a\nwhich is regarded as a return of the n\ndisease from which he suffered three L\nyears ago, when he went to Philadelphia P\nto consult specialists.\nPhysician's Statement.\nDr. J. W. Babock. one of his physi- j,\nclans, issued the following statement this f\nafternoon: q\n\"Senator Tillman was taken seriously n\nill Thursday night. He spoke Monday -c\nat Washington, and after two days at\nClemson College he went to his home\nat Trenton, complaining of the heat.\nThat night he had an attack, ev'dently\ndue to hard work and the unusual heat, S\nwhich produced nervous trouble similar p\nto that from which he suffered three\nyears ago, whm he consulted with specialists\nin Philadelphia, who found no\nsigns of organic disease. After a short b\nrest the senator was soon at his post again.\nIn the present attack the symp- n\nterns of the old numbness and tingling s\nof the left side have returned, but they\nhave lessened in the last twenty-four 11\nhours.\"\nALIA \"IS SENTENCED j\nMURDERER OF FR. LEO HEINRICHS\nHEARS HIS DOOM.\na\nn\nDENVER, March 21.?Giuseppe Alia,\nmurderer of Father Leo Heinrichs, was\nremoved this afternoon from the Den- i'j\nver jail to the slate prison at Canyon js\nCity, there to be hanged during the h\nweek beginning July 12.\nJust four weeks from the Sunday\nmorning when he shot the priest at\nearly mass in St. Elizabeth's Catholic r\nChurch, in Denver, after kneeling at v\nthe altar rail and receiving the -sacred\nwater, me assassin will awake in sou- j\ntary confinement, which will continue j\nduring- the sixteen remaining weeks of i\nhis life.\nGoes Under Guard. c\nThe condemned man presented a pitiable\nappearance when haled in court\ntoday to hear his doom pronounced by\nJudge Greely W. Whitford. His head t\nwas scratched and battered from beat- c\ning it against the bars of his cell door.\nHe was. or feigned to be, too weak to\nstand alone. He was supported by two\nofficers while listening to his sentence.\nMuttering, \"I never harmed ciny one.\"\nthe prisoner was half dragged, half\ncarried, from the jail to a carriage, in g\nwhich he was driven to the station and\nplaced aboard a train for Canyon City.\nAlia's arms and legs were .-.hackled, 1\nand he was accompanied by a double G\nguard on the journey. c\nt\nI\ni PI DINNER.\n:'mW 'Ijtj^HHB\nflj\nna\nV <f:\n29^^ft i*v, $*^flBs&?[EHHl\n}JfEWY SHEEMAN TxjJJTELL\nor Illinois i\n>anic is still a matter of dispute. Eut I\nhis much is certain, those scenes of law- I\nessness, recklessness, frenzy, theft, re-\nlentance and suicide were not of the B\nleople's making. This much more is Q\nertain, it was the deposits of the people, I\nhe small earnings of those of moderate I\nneans which were used to stay (he I\nrightful disaster inaugurated by the dar- I\nng and recklessness of those leading B\nusine#s men. It was the revelry of the H\nliosen few. While the great mass of ra\nhe people throughout this broad land, H\natient and forbearing, paying but little I\nttention to this disturbance on the roof B\nnrden of finance, tolled on and by I\nourage and conservatism did more to H\niring back confidence than all el3e. If I\nhe masses had become excited as did 9\nhose few hundred about the centers of a\nonservative business places there would I\nave been a holocaust of indescribable\nuin from ocean to ocean.\n4 I have no patience with that species _\nf artless demagogue which inveighs\ngainst the rich because they are rich, il\nrhich arraigns corporate wealth honestly U\nbtained and honestly used, which wars\npon the fruit of industry and frugality.\n\"Now in the midst of the most remarkble\nand momentous civic struggle the\nwestern world has ever known, involving\nuestlons which reach down to the very\noundation of government and upon the\nroper solution of which depends the wea'\nr Svoe of 90.00u.000 of people?a struggle Sj\nailing for courage as rare and patriotism\ns exceptional as any since this old ship\ntarted on her voyage, the industrious\nlisciples of that old school, true to their\nraditions. cursed with the same want\nf faith, are telling in the same old tones\nf the fearful consequences which never\nlappen.\n\"But when the test and trial are passed 11\nnd only the large outlines of today's sc\nistory are given again, it will be rewrlten\nupon another heroic page that in ac\npite of doubts and fears, in spite of si\nV? n f f Via erreot\nuuic mtaianca a\"u ciiw?a, mat w*w\niass of the people remained true to the\nest tenets of representative government; w\nhat we were not engaged In a revolution, ei\nut marking a mile-stone In evolution.\" ci\nAmong the university chapters repre- Q)\nented at the dinner were those of Rut:ers,\nYale. Stevens. Pennsylvania. Lehigh\nnd Columbia. Among those at the guests' a'\nibla were Representative Charles B. Lan- q\\\n's of Indiana. Representative Scott of\nCansas. Rev. Robert W. Courtney and\nIncwlton Burham.\nSenator Borah's reference to the next tr\nlominee of the republican party for Pres- m\nSent as sure to be one \"who represents\nhe policies of President Roosevelt\"\nirought a storm of applause from his\n.uditors. la\nle\niOCK CREEK PARK\n01\ng<\nI ILL FOB ADDITION PASSED BY J\nSENATE YESTERDAY. ta\n_________ m\nIn\nSenator Scott of West Virginia, chair- n<\nian of the committee on public buildings\nnd grounds, stole a march on Senator\nlean of New Jersey yesterday afternoon\nList before the Senate adjourned by\nringing up in Mr. Kean's absence the\nlallinger bill to acquire land in Hall and\nllvan's subdivision of Meridian Hill in\nhe District for a public park and getting\npassed without a dissenting voice. The\nther day when this bill was reached 6\nn the calendar. Mr. Kean prevented it a'\nrom being considered on the ground that\nI carried too big an appropriation.\nThe proposed park is to include the land \"V\nat nman F110IM r??t. u?_\nuli-.ou olic;i. <.uiuuiui<t roafi or\n5th street, W street or Florida avenue\nnd 16th street extended, containing in the j\nggregate 437,000 square feet approxi- ,v\nlately. To pay for the land and the\nimprovements thereon $550,000 is approriated.\nj\nAnother bill from the public buildings\nnd grounds committee got through easily\nesterday afternoon when nobody was\nooking. This was the Gallinger bill\nor a one-hundred-acre addition to Rock\nIreek Park, to extend the park to the\naval observatory grounds. The exact\nioundaries of the proposed addition have\nieen published in The Star. An appro- 'J<\nnation of $423,000 is carried in the bill. Tr\nBoth of these park bills passed the 1\nlenate last year and were held up in the vv\nlouse.\nA third Gallinger bill got through at\nhe same time. This is the bill amending\nan act to provide for the extension of\niew Hampshire avenue. The amendment\nstrikes out the provisioin for a S\ntraight extension and provides instead\nor an extension in accordance wdth the\nilghway plans for the city.\nG\nSPRINGFIELD CHOSEN.\nL\n*lace of the National Amateur \"Rj?- P\ngatta. N\nNEW YORK. March 21,-Springtield,\nlass., was tonight selected as the place\nnd August 14 and 15 the dates for the g\natlonal regatta of the NationaJ Associa- pi\nion of Amateur Oarsmen of America,\n'he meeting of the national committee vl\n.as held at the New York Athletic Club. v'\n'he Harlem Regatta Association and the\niaratoga Association were the only other vi\nidders for the regatta. ai\nGov. Guild Unchanged. S\nBOSTON, March 21.?Gov. Curtis Guild\n>assed a comfortable day and evening. y\nvlthout tbe slightest change in his general\nconditiori being detected by his 3\nihysiclans. The last bulletin of the night\nssued by Dr. Frederick B. Wlnslow at K\n0:30, follows:\n\"The governor's condition is still un:hanged.\nHe is resting comfortably.\"\nS\nSenator Bryan's Condition. b<\nReports from Providence Hospital early\nhis morning, are to the effect that the\n:ondltion of Senator Bryan of Florida,\nvho Is 111 of typhoid fever, is slightly lm- F\n>roved.\nS\nDenver Convention Fund. c\nDENVER, Col.. March 21.?A draft for g\n25.00f? was mailed today by the Denver\nlonventlon League to the democratic ri\nlatlonal committee, completing the $100,- Y\nno fund subscribed to bring the national S.\nonventlon to Denver. 8:\nStores Close {f0\"\n\nChoice Fo\nSpecial\nThis\nSpring Oxfords and Shoes\nGirls and the Little Folks. Ye\nare crowded with the latest nc\nCalf, one, two and three buckle:\nO w.-> Tj ofanf C <-\\1 f \\T 1 i\nvjvmucu ujuv\\ii, i aain v_.wn,\nlatest styles in Pumps in all le\ngo to make honest footwear ai\nbuy here, whether you pay $i.c\nwell and wear well.\nLadles' $4.00 Oxfords and Shoes In Patent\nColt. Gun Metal. Tan. Russian Calf\nand Viei kid: Cuban. Military and French\nheels; button, blucher and s\nlaced styles. Many choice 7 f\\II\nand elegant styles. Special V/\nLadles' $5.00 and $rt.<>0 Oxfords and\nShoes In all leathers: tub^n. military ami\nFrench heels. All th? latest and most upto-date\nstyles. Button. a mm\nblucher and laced. SpeLadles'\n$1'.50 Oxfords and Shoes in Vicl\nKid. Patent. Tan. Both\nlight and heavy soles. Styl- f m\nish and comfortable lasts. *K I f\nSpecial\nLadies' $1.75 Shoes; Vlcl Kid aud Box\nCalf; light weight; also\nheavy 60les: bluc