AND EDUCATION\nSUBJECT OF DISCUSSION.\nPresident Macfarland of Board of\nCommissioners Asks Society's Aid\nin Combating Bookmakers.\nAt a gathering of the Daughters of the\nAmerican Revolution of the District of\nColumbia in the library at the New Wlllard\nlast evening reports from the subcommittee\non \"Patriotic Education\" were\nread and addressee were made in support\nof their respective movements.\nThe meeting was called to order by the\nstate regent, Mrs. Howard L. Hodgkins, i\nwho invited the vice president general.\nMrs. Ellen Spencer Mussey, chairman of\nthe general commltte on patriotic education\nto take the chair. Mrs. Mussey\naccepted and introduced Commissioner H.\nB. F. Macfarland.\nMr. Macfarland addressed himself to\nthe subject of the child labor law.\n\"Some folks think.\" said he. \"that there\nis no need of such a law in this community.\n\"We have in the compulsory education\nlaw a provision which does something\ntoward regulating child labor in the District.\nand experience has shown that\nmuch good has been accomplished by It.\nWe had a compulsory education law In\nforce for many years, but it had as many\nloopholes to it as the present anti-gambling\nlaws.\" He then urged the ladles\npresent and the D. A. R. generally to do\nall that was in their power to assist the\nCommissioners to protect the nation's\ncapital from the bookmakers who come\nhere twice a year and who, he said, carry\naway with them each time a quarter of a\nmillion of the people's money.\n\"We need laws to protect the future.\"\nhe said. \"The time may come when the\nworst conditions that prevail elsewhere\nmay arise here, and there is ample argument\nnow for the enactment of a child\nlabor law.\"\nMrs. Mussey called attention to the fact\nthat under the compulsory education law\nthere were three truant officers to look\nafter flO.OOO children.\nMrs. Bushee, the chief truant officer,\nread an address covering her work and\nreciting instances to show the need of a\nlaw such as proposed. Mrs. Mussey announced\nthe establishment of twelve special\nschools, which some call \"Ellen Spencer\nMussey Schools,\" she said, where part\nof the course is academic and the rest\ndevoted to a special wdrk. such as weaving.\npainting and the like. She described\nsome of the beautiful work whtrh\nhad been done at these schools. They\nhave been allowed by Congress the use of\n$5,000 for this special work.\nMiss Elizabeth F. Pierce, chairman of\nthe Juvenile and probationary work committee,\ntold of the progress that had been\nmade and the efforts that were being\nmade in those lines.\nThe Juvenile Court.\nMrs. J. Ellen Foster described the object\nand the workings of the Juvenile\nCourt under Judge DeLacy, which deals\nwith the child who. without malice, commits\na crime, by suspending sentence and\nholding it over his head as a punishment\nto be meted out If the offense is repeated.\nSeveral instances were related of cases\nthat arose in the court where by this\nmethod great good had been accomplished.\nAt the request of Mrs. L. H. Mattingly.\nMrs. Giles Scott Rafter, acsistant supervisor\nof playgrounds, was introduced and\ngave an interesting address upon playgrounds\nfor the children. She said that\nthere were twenty-si* playgrounds, but\nthere was not a single American flag for\nany of them, and asked that the D. A.\nI R. see to It that the flag was provided for\nthem all. Mrs. Mattingly announced that\nafter the close of the met no- ho. om\"\nmittee would assemble and take action\nIn the matter. Addresses were also made\nby Mrs. Morgan D. Lewis, chairman of\nthe committee on \"children of the republic;\"\nMrs. Smallwood. who spoke upon\nthe same subject; Miss Thayer of the As-\nsociated Charities, who described how the i\nwork of aii Italian club, which originated\nin an alley in the southeast section *as\nbeing conducted, and Mrs. Pepper, directress\nof the school, along the same\nline. At the conclusion of the addresses a\nshort business session was held to discuss\nroutine matters, and the meeting\nthen adjourned.\nDANIEL C. OSMUN\" DEAD.\nRetired Fire Insurance Official Suddenly\nExpires.\nDaniel C. Osmun, a winter resident of\nthis city during the past three years, died\nsuddenly last night about 10 o'clock at\nhis boarding house, 134H 14th street northwest.\nof apoplexy. He was a retired\ntiro insurance official, having been for\nmany years secretary of the Northwest\nFire Underwriters' Union of Chicago.\nHis wife was with him when lie died.\nThey had been out for a walk only a\nfew minutes before.\nMr Osmun was a native of New Jersey\nand was seventy-four years of age. He\nI came to this city from Chicago, his former\nhome. Besides his wife he leaves\nI one son. who lives in Chicago.\nFuneral services will be held over his\nj remains Tuesday in this city, tfhd Interment\nwill be made later at Orange, N. J.\nf","height":"38180","width":"27204"}}
